import heapq

class KthLargest:

    def __init__(self, k, nums):
        self.heap = []
        self.k = k
        for num in nums:
            self.add(num)

    def add(self, val):
        heapq.heappush(self.heap, val)
        if len(self.heap) > self.k:
            heapq.heappop(self.heap)
        return self.heap[0]
```

    The algorithm uses a priority queue called a min heap to keep track of the top `k` largest elements of the stream. For each element added to the stream, it is added to the min heap. If the size of min heap exceeds `k`, then the smallest element in the min heap (which is the top of the min heap) is removed. This ensures that the min heap always contains the `k` largest elements in the stream. Finally, when we want to find the kth largest element, we simply return the smallest element in the min heap (i.e., the top of the min heap).

